Paraśurāma: his hybrid status as a Brahmin warrior, his act of matricide, and his bloody one-man war to cleanse the earth of Kṣatriyas. Collins considers a wide variety of representations of the myth, from its origins in the Mahābhārata to contemporary debates online. He also examines Paraśurāma alongside the Wandering Jew of European legend and Psycho's matricidal serial killer Norman Bates. He examines why mythmakers once elevated this transgressive and antisocial figure to the level of an avatāra and why he still holds such fascination for a world that continues to grapple with mass killings and violence against women.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aGenocidexReligious aspects. 0aHindu mythology. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Literature. 4aAsian Studies : India and South Asian Studies. 4aPsychology : Psychological Approaches to Literature. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Comparative Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Hindu Studies. 7aRELIGION / Hinduism / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2020z978311149149340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848040440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438480404423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438480404/original  a978-3-11-149149-3  SUNY Press eBook Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles